commit b2f907bf8ccd82e7e56059da369605544aa26920
Author: NOGUCHI Shoji <57870202+ngc-shj@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Thu Apr 30 20:47:57 2026 +0900

    perf(hooks): consolidate per-hook jq calls (2 -> 1) via U+001F separator (#39)
    
    Cut the Bash chain latency from ~77ms to ~42ms cumulative (-45%) by
    emitting both `tool_name` and `tool_input.command` from a single jq
    invocation per hook, separated by U+001F (Unit Separator), and
    splitting via bash parameter expansion.
    
    Each block-* hook on the Bash matcher previously did two `jq -r`
    invocations (one for tool_name, one for command). Now:
    
      PARSED=$(echo "$INPUT" | jq -rj '(.tool_name // ""), "", (.tool_input.command // "")')
      TOOL_NAME="${PARSED%%$'\x1f'*}"
      COMMAND="${PARSED#*$'\x1f'}"
    
    Why U+001F (Unit Separator) instead of `@tsv`:
    
    The earlier `@tsv` attempt during PR #29 was reverted because jq's
    @tsv format escapes embedded TABs in field values as the literal
    two characters "\\t" (backslash + t), so a command like
    `docker\tcompose down -v` (legitimate via $'docker\tcompose...')
    arrived at the regex with `\\t` instead of an actual TAB, breaking
    the `[[:space:]]+` match in the docker hook.
    
    `jq -rj '..., "", ...'` emits a real 0x1F byte AND preserves
    embedded control chars (including TAB) in the field values
    verbatim. U+001F is virtually never present in real shell commands,
    so the field-split is unambiguous.
    
    Bash parameter expansion (`${var%%pat*}` / `${var#*pat}`) replaces
    `read -r` for splitting — both are pure bash and preserve newlines
    and special chars in the value half.
    
    Files changed:
      hooks/block-destructive-docker.sh
      hooks/block-vcs-history-rewrite.sh
      hooks/block-audit-observability-destruction.sh
      hooks/block-recovery-path-destruction.sh
      hooks/block-secret-key-destruction.sh
      hooks/block-authz-state-destruction.sh
    
    Verification:
    - bats tests/ -> 341/341 pass (no regression). The block-destructive-
      docker.bats `docker\tcompose down -v` (tab whitespace) case still
      passes — the earlier reason for reverting @tsv does not apply here.
    - New benchmark recorded at docs/archive/bench/hook-latency-2026-04-
      30-after-jq-consolidation.md: per-hook avg dropped from ~12-14ms
      to ~7ms, Bash chain cumulative 77ms -> 42ms (-45%).
    - Updated tests/bench-hooks.sh script Notes section to reflect the
      consolidation (replaces the "future optimization candidate" note
      with the post-consolidation context).
    
    Co-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

